ARTICLE.TITLE: This is where UK holidaymakers stand after government advised against travel to France
ARTICLE.TEXT:
Sign up to receive two FREE daily bulletin e-mails, as well as breaking news as it happens Subscribe Thank you for subscribing We have more newsletters Show me See our privacy notice Invalid Email

The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is now advising against all but essential travel to France, over fears of growing numbers of coronavirus infections in the country.

From 4am on Saturday, any British travellers in France or returning from the country will be required to self-isolate for 14 days when they arrive back in the UK.

The bad news for anyone with a holiday booked to France is that it is likely to be cancelled - so this is what experts have recommended is the best course of action, reports MirrorOnline.

The first thing is to contact your tour operator, travel firm or travel agent. You are entitled to a refund if your airline or package holiday is cancelled.

Some airlines may still operate services may still go ahead despite the UK government advice, so if your flight isn't cancelled you may have to negotiate with your airline.

Seevral carriers have been offering vouchers or the option to re-book for a later date instead.

For package holidays, travel companies are offering a range of options, which include a refund as well as other options such as re-booking the same trip for a later date, or being offered credit/vouchers to use with them on a future holiday.

Anyone who has booked a flight and accommodation separately, may need to negotiate. It is possible that holidaymakers may not offered a full refund, but may receive vouchers for future trips.

You can find out more in our full guide to refund rights following the change of France travel advice.

Because of the sheer number of travellers affected by cancelled trips during the pandemic, some firms are prioritising holidaymakers who are scheduled to travel during the coming weeks.

If you have a trip planned that is some time ahead, it could be that you will be asked to get in touch again closer to the departure date.

Those with an existing policy taken out before the pandemic, may be covered for out of pocket losses. Check your policy details and get in touch with your insurance provider.
